alse}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115153","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115153"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic for review. Her medical history includes hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus, and heart failure with preserved ejection fraction. Her medications are perindopril 10mg daily, chlorthalidone 25mg daily and amlodipine 10mg daily. On examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 70/min, blood pressure 162/94 mmHg without postural drop, and BMI 31 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. There are vesicular breath sounds throughout the lung fields, jugular venous pressure is 1cm and there is bilateral lower limb swelling to the ankles. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which medication should be commenced next?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Extended release metoprolol","Candesartan","Hydrochlorothiazide","Moxonidine","Sacubitril/Valsartan"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has resistant hypertension, defined as blood pressure that remains above target despite concurrent use of three antihypertensive agents of different classes. The most appropriate next step in management is to commence\u003Cstrong\u003E extended release metoprolol\u003C/strong\u003E, a beta-blocker, as a fourth-line agent. Beta-blockers are recommended as an additional therapy when first-line treatments (ACE inhibitors, calcium channel blockers, and thiazide diuretics) are inadequate to control blood pressure. In this case, selection of a cardioselective \u03b2 blocker such as extended release metoprolol may also have additional benefits for this patients heart failure management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECandesartan\u003C/strong\u003E is an angiotensin II receptor blocker (ARB). The patient is already taking maximum dose of an ACE inhibitor. It is not appropriate to commence both an ACE inhibitor and ARB in combination due to potentiation of side effects including hypotension and hyperkalaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESacubitril/Valsartan\u003C/strong\u003E is an angiotensin II receptor blocker-neprolysin inhibitor (ARNI). It is an incorrect option for the reason listed above. In addition, ARNI is only listed on PBS for the indication of heart failure with reduced ejection fraction, alongside other criteria, noting the patient in the stem has heart failure with preserved ejection fraction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydrochlorothiazide\u003C/strong\u003E is less correct as the patient is already on a thiazide diuretic - chlorthalidone. Adding a different class of medication (such as a beta blocker or mineralocorticoid receptor antagonist) is a more correct option. Combining two thiazide diuretics is not advised, due to potentiation of side effects including hyponatraemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMoxonidine\u003C/strong\u003E is a centrally acting anti-hypertensive agent that is relatively contraindicated in heart failure (as demonstrated in clinical trials including the MOXCON trial).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to adding a \u03b2 blocker, it is important to emphasise lifestyle modifications such as sodium restriction, weight loss, regular exercise, and limiting alcohol intake. The patient\u0027s elevated BMI suggests that weight loss could contribute significantly to blood pressure control. Additionally, ensure medication adherence and consider secondary causes of hypertension if blood pressure remains uncontrolled despite these interventions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Resistant hypertension is defined as blood pressure that remains above goal despite concurrent use of three antihypertensive agents of different classes.","Beta blockers can reduce heart rate and blood pressure.","Lifestyle modifications, including sodium restriction and weight loss, should be emphasised alongside pharmacological treatment for hypertension."],"references":["Blood pressure: measure, manage, monitor. In: NPS MedicineWise [online]. 2015 [cited 2024 Aug 4]. Available from: https://www.nps.org.au/news/blood-pressure-measure-manage-monitor"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97161"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14031"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97161","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97161"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-22T16:30:47+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-22T16:32:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6680"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115153"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links"